            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Solis is a cornerstone of her Hayes Valley community, as much a fixture as the linden trees lining the sidewalks. The daughter of Filipino immigrants, she grew up in Daly City, where the fog was a constant companion and practicality was preached over passion. Her mother, a seamstress, could miraculously replicate designer looks from magazine clippings, instilling in Priya an early appreciation for the structure and story behind every garment. While her parents hoped for a stable career in nursing or administration, Priya was drawn to the expressive world of fashion.\n\nShe pursued a degree in Fashion Merchandising and landed a promising buyer position at a major Union Square department store. For a decade, she navigated the corporate world, learning the business of trends and turnover. However, she felt a growing disconnect from the soulless pace of fast fashion. The pivotal moment came with a layoff during the dot-com bust of the early 2000s. With her severance and savings, Priya took a monumental risk, leasing a small, affordable storefront in a still-developing Hayes Valley, recently opened up by the removal of a freeway overpass. She named it \"Chroma Vintage.\"\n\nOver two decades, Priya and her boutique have grown with the neighborhood. Chroma Vintage is her sanctuary, a curated collection of pieces from the 1940s to the 1990s, each with a history she loves to share. Her 0.8-mile walk to work is a daily ritual, a tranquil journey past familiar faces and fellow small business owners.\n\nAt 51, Priya shares her life and a tastefully restored Victorian flat with her partner of 22 years, Marco, an architect. They are a beloved neighborhood couple, often found enjoying a glass of wine at a local bar or attending a performance at the nearby SFJAZZ Center. Her aspirations are no longer about growth but about legacy. She dreams of mentoring a young, passionate buyer to eventually take over Chroma Vintage, ensuring its spirit endures. For Priya, success isn't measured in revenue, but in the beauty she preserves and the community she has helped build, one perfect vintage dress at a time."
